{"title_page": "Desire\u00e9 Cousteau", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name            = Desire\u00e9 Cousteau\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = \n| birth_place     = <!--[[Savannah, Georgia]], [[United States]] (unsourced)-->\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| occupation      = Pornographic actress\n| years_active    = 1978\u20131986\n| known_for       = \n| spouse          = \n| height          = \n| weight          = \n| alias           = \n| website         = \n}}\n'''Desire\u00e9 Cousteau''' was the stage name of a former [[pornographic actress]] of the 1970s and 1980s. She is best known for her roles in the 1978 film ''[[Pretty Peaches]]'' and 1979's ''Inside D\u00e9sir\u00e9e Cousteau''. In 1993, she was inducted into the [[XRCO Hall of Fame]],<ref>\"The XRCO Hall of Fame\", ''Adam Film World Guide 1994 Directory of Adult Films'', p. 57</ref> and in 1997, she was inducted into the [[List of members of the AVN Hall of Fame|AVN Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avnawards.com/halloffame.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415212412/http://www.avnawards.com/halloffame.php|title=AVN Awards Hall of Fame - official listing - archived April 15, 2009|archivedate=15 April 2009|work=avnawards.com|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCousteau aspired to be a mainstream [[Model (person)|model]], but was deemed to not be tall and thin enough.<ref name=\"TSBT\">{{cite news |last1=Emmons |first1=Becky |title=Star of X-rated films wants to upgrade 'art' |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31731132/the_south_bend_tribune/ |accessdate=19 May 2019 |publisher=The South Bend Tribune |date=11 September 1981}}</ref> She began to model lingerie before eventually posing for [[Penthouse (magazine)|Penthouse magazine]].<ref name=\"TSBT\"/> She also attempted a career as a mainstream actress, landing a small part in the 1974 \"[[women in prison]]\" [[B-movie]] ''[[Caged Heat]]''.<ref name=\"CP\">{{cite news |last1=Ettinger |first1=Stewart |title=Desiree Cousteau is one of the best paid erotic stars |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29895821/ |accessdate=27 March 2019 |publisher=Courier-Post |date=7 November 1980}}</ref> Her career stagnated and she tired of being sexually propositioned for parts, so she soon began appearing in sex films after being asked by adult film director [[Alex de Renzy]] to appear in ''Pretty Peaches''.<ref name=\"CP\"/><ref name=\"TSBT\"/> She was usually typecast in sweet, dizzy, na\u00efve roles.<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Kent |last2=Moore |first2=Darrell W. |last3=Reagle |first3=Merl |title=Adult Movies |date=1983 |publisher=Pocket Books (Mm) |isbn=9780671468446 |page=65 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7sfrAAAAMAAJ&dq=%220-671-46844-8%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Desiree+Cousteau |accessdate=27 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref> She worked steadily in adult movies from the late 1970s through the early 1980s.\n\nShe received the [[Adult Film Association of America#Best Actress|Adult Film Association of America Best Actress]] Award in 1979 for her performance in the movie ''Pretty Peaches'',<ref name=\"TSBT\"/><ref name=\"hs1179\">\"Silver Spoonfuls: A Star Is Porn,\" ''High Society'' magazine, November 1979, pp. 8-9.</ref><ref name=\"afw0180\">Jules Griffon, \"The Third Annual Erotica Awards\", ''Adam Film World'', Vol. 7, No. 8, January 1980, pp. 24\u201327.</ref> with film director Alex de Renzy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explodingkinetoscope.blogspot.com/2006/09/all-american-deep-dish-comedy-pretty.html|title=The Exploding Kinetoscope: All-American Deep-Dish Comedy: PRETTY PEACHES (1978)|work=explodingkinetoscope.blogspot.com|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Golden Age of Porn]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|first=Nicolas|last=Barbano|title=Verdens 25 hotteste pornostjerner|publisher=Rosinante|location=[[Denmark]]|year=1999|isbn=87-7357-961-0}} - includes a chapter on Cousteau.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0184149|Desiree Cousteau}}\n* {{iafd name|id=Cousteau|gender=female|name=Desiree Cousteau}}\n* {{afdb name|id=4181|gender=female|name=Desiree Cousteau}}\n\n{{Pornography}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cousteau, Desiree}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American pornographic film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name            = Desire\u00e9 Cousteau\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = \n| birth_place     = <!--[[Savannah, Georgia]], USA (unsourced)-->\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| occupation      = Pornographic actress\n| years_active    = 1978\u20131986\n| known_for       = \n| spouse          = \n| height          = \n| weight          = \n| alias           = \n| website         = \n}}\n'''Desire\u00e9 Cousteau''' was the stage name of a former [[pornographic actress]] of the 1970s and 1980s. She is best known for her roles in the 1978 film ''[[Pretty Peaches]]'' and 1979's ''Inside D\u00e9sir\u00e9e Cousteau''. In 1993, she was inducted into the [[XRCO Hall of Fame]],<ref>\"The XRCO Hall of Fame\", ''Adam Film World Guide 1994 Directory of Adult Films'', p. 57</ref> and, in 1997, she was inducted into the [[List of members of the AVN Hall of Fame|AVN Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avnawards.com/halloffame.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415212412/http://www.avnawards.com/halloffame.php|title=AVN Awards Hall of Fame - official listing - archived April 15, 2009|archivedate=15 April 2009|work=avnawards.com|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCousteau aspired to be an mainstream model, but was deemed to not be tall and thin enough.<ref name=\"TSBT\">{{cite news |last1=Emmons |first1=Becky |title=Star of X-rated films wants to upgrade 'art' |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31731132/the_south_bend_tribune/ |accessdate=19 May 2019 |publisher=The South Bend Tribune |date=11 September 1981}}</ref> She began to model lingerie before eventually posing for [[Penthouse (magazine)|Penthouse magazine]].<ref name=\"TSBT\"/> She also attempted a career as a mainstream actress, landing a small part in the 1974 \"[[women in prison]]\" [[B-movie]] ''[[Caged Heat]]''.<ref name=\"CP\">{{cite news |last1=Ettinger |first1=Stewart |title=Desiree Cousteau is one of the best paid erotic stars |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29895821/ |accessdate=27 March 2019 |publisher=Courier-Post |date=7 November 1980}}</ref> Her career stagnated and she tired of being sexually propositioned for parts, so she soon began appearing in sex films after being asked by adult film director [[Alex de Renzy]] to appear in ''Pretty Peaches''.<ref name=\"CP\"/><ref name=\"TSBT\"/> She was usually typecast in sweet, dizzy, na\u00efve roles.<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Kent |last2=Moore |first2=Darrell W. |last3=Reagle |first3=Merl |title=Adult Movies |date=1983 |publisher=Pocket Books (Mm) |isbn=9780671468446 |page=65 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7sfrAAAAMAAJ&dq=%220-671-46844-8%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Desiree+Cousteau |accessdate=27 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref> She worked steadily in adult movies from the late 1970s through the early 1980s.\n\nShe received the [[Adult Film Association of America#Best Actress|Adult Film Association of America Best Actress]] Award in 1979 for her performance in the movie ''Pretty Peaches'',<ref name=\"TSBT\"/><ref name=\"hs1179\">\"Silver Spoonfuls: A Star Is Porn,\" ''High Society'' magazine, November 1979, pp. 8-9.</ref><ref name=\"afw0180\">Jules Griffon, \"The Third Annual Erotica Awards\", ''Adam Film World'', Vol. 7, No. 8, January 1980, pp. 24\u201327.</ref> with film director Alex de Renzy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explodingkinetoscope.blogspot.com/2006/09/all-american-deep-dish-comedy-pretty.html|title=The Exploding Kinetoscope: All-American Deep-Dish Comedy: PRETTY PEACHES (1978)|work=explodingkinetoscope.blogspot.com|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Golden Age of Porn]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|first=Nicolas|last=Barbano|title=Verdens 25 hotteste pornostjerner|publisher=Rosinante|location=[[Denmark]]|year=1999|isbn=87-7357-961-0}} - includes a chapter on Cousteau.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0184149|Desiree Cousteau}}\n* {{iafd name|id=Cousteau|gender=female|name=Desiree Cousteau}}\n* {{afdb name|id=4181|gender=female|name=Desiree Cousteau}}\n\n{{Pornography}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cousteau, Desiree}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American pornographic film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n", "name_user": "StanchevFPS", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desire%C3%A9_Cousteau"}
{"title_page": "Face masks during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{short description|Aspect of ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Merge portions from|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Public use of face masks|discuss=Talk:Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Split the public use of face masks section|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:04.02_\u7e3d\u7d71\u8996\u5bdf\u300c\u4e2d\u592e\u6d41\u884c\u75ab\u60c5\u6307\u63ee\u4e2d\u5fc3\u300d_49726568957_66543b616e_o.jpg|thumb|[[Taiwan]] President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] wearing a mask.]]\nThe wearing of face masks during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has received varying recommendations from different [[List of national public health agencies|public health agencies]] and governments. The topic has been a subject of debate, with various public health agencies and governments disagreeing on a protocol for wearing face masks. Some recommend that all members of the public wear masks, while others recommend that only [[COVID-19]] patients and their caretakers should wear masks. Additionally, public health agencies of different countries and territories have often changed their recommendations regarding face masks over time.<ref name=\"mask_not_mask\"/> Face masks have been a subject of [[shortage]]s, and also been made compulsory in some countries. \n\nTypes of face masks, from least to most protective, include [[cloth face mask]]s, medical (non-surgical) masks,<ref name=\"nhc_masks\" /><ref name=20200402businessinsider/> [[surgical masks]], and filtering facepiece [[respirator]]s such as [[N95 mask]]s and [[FFP mask]]s. [[Face shield]]s and medical [[goggles]] are other types of protective equipment often used together with face masks.\n\n==Types of masks==\n[[File:HomemadeFacemask.jpg|thumb|Homemade [[cloth face mask]]]]\nA [[cloth face mask]] is a mask made of a common [[textile]], usually [[cotton]], worn over the mouth and nose. Unlike surgical masks and respirators, they are not subject to regulation, and there is currently little research or guidance on their effectiveness as a protective measure against [[Transmission (medicine)|infectious disease transmission]] or [[Particulates|particulate]] [[air pollution]].{{cn|date=April 2020}} They were routinely used by healthcare workers starting from the late 19th century until the mid 20th century. In the 1960s they fell out of use in the [[Developed country|developed world]] in favor of modern surgical masks, but their use has persisted in [[Developing country|developing countries]].<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://www.nap.edu/catalog/11637|title=Reusability of Facemasks During an Influenza Pandemic: Facing the Flu|date=2006-07-24|publisher=National Academies Press|isbn=978-0-309-10182-0|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=6, 36\u201338|doi=10.17226/11637}}</ref><ref name=\":03\">{{Cite journal|last=MacIntyre|first=C. R.|last2=Chughtai|first2=A. A.|date=2015-04-09|title=Facemasks for the prevention of infection in healthcare and community settings|url=http://akkie.mods.jp/2019-nCoV/images/c/c0/%E3%82%B5%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B8%E3%82%AB%E3%83%AB%E3%83%9E%E3%82%B9%E3%82%AF%E5%8C%BB%E7%99%82vs%E5%B8%82%E4%B8%AD%E6%84%9F%E6%9F%93%E4%BA%88%E9%98%B2%EF%BC%9A%E7%B7%8F%E8%AA%AC_%282015%2C_MacIntyre%29.pdf|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=350|issue=apr09 1|pages=h694|doi=10.1136/bmj.h694|pmid=25858901|issn=1756-1833|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Chughtai|first=Abrar Ahmad|last2=Seale|first2=Holly|last3=MacIntyre|first3=Chandini Raina|date=2013-06-19|title=Use of cloth masks in the practice of infection control \u2013 evidence and policy gaps|url=http://www.ijic.info/article/view/11366|journal=International Journal of Infection Control|volume=9|issue=3|doi=10.3396/IJIC.v9i3.020.13|issn=1996-9783}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Surgical face mask.jpg|thumb|A [[surgical mask]]]]\nA [[surgical mask]] is a loose-fitting, [[Disposable product|disposable]] device that creates a physical barrier between the mouth and nose of the wearer and potential [[Contamination|contaminants]] in the immediate environment. If worn properly, a surgical mask is meant to help block large-particle [[Respiratory droplets|droplets]], splashes, [[Spray (liquid drop)|sprays]], or splatter that may contain [[virus]]es and [[bacteria]], keeping it from reaching the wearer's mouth and nose. Surgical masks may also help reduce exposure of the wearer's [[saliva]] and respiratory secretions to others.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fda.gov/medical-devices/personal-protective-equipment-infection-control/n95-respirators-and-surgical-masks-face-masks|title=N95 Respirators and Surgical Masks (Face Masks)|last=|first=|date=2020-03-11|website=U.S. Food and Drug Administration|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-28}} {{PD-inline}}</ref> A surgical mask, by design, does not filter or block very small particles in the air that may be transmitted by coughs, sneezes, or certain medical procedures. Surgical masks also do not provide complete protection from [[Pathogen|germs]] and other contaminants because of the loose fit between the surface of the face mask and the face. Surgical masks may be labeled as surgical, isolation, dental, or medical procedure masks.<ref name=\":2\" /> Surgical masks are made of a [[nonwoven fabric]] created using a [[melt blowing]] process.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/03/05/811387424/face-masks-not-enough-are-made-in-america-to-deal-with-coronavirus|title=Not Enough Face Masks Are Made In America To Deal With Coronavirus|date=2020-03-05|website=NPR.org|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/09e13687-f7e1-485e-ba90-355959449c71|title=Chinese mask makers use loopholes to speed up regulatory approval|date=2020-04-01|website=Financial Times|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n[[File:3M_N95_Particulate_Respirator.JPG|right|thumb|An [[N95 mask]]]]\nAn [[N95 mask]] is a particulate-filtering facepiece [[respirator]] that meets the N95 [[NIOSH air filtration rating|air filtration rating]] of the US [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]], meaning that it filters at least 95 percent of [[airborne particles]], while not resistant to [[oil]] like the P95. It is the most common particulate-filtering facepiece respirator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/npptl/topics/respirators/disp_part/n95list1-a.html|title=NIOSH-Approved N95 Particulate Filtering Facepiece Respirators - A Suppliers List|last=|first=|date=2020-03-19|website=U.S. National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> It is an example of a [[mechanical filter respirator]], which provides protection against [[particulates]], but not [[gas]]es or [[vapor]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/npptl/topics/respirators/disp_part/respsource3selection.html|title=Respirator Trusted-Source: Selection FAQs|last=|first=|date=2020-03-12|website=U.S. National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Like surgical masks, the N95 mask is made of melt-blown nonwoven polypropylene fabric.<ref name=\"VOADeliver\">{{Cite news|last=Zie|first=John |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/world-depends-china-face-masks-can-country-deliver|title=World Depends on China for Face Masks But Can Country Deliver? |date=March 19, 2020|newspaper=[[Voice of America]]|accessdate=|authorlink=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Feng|first=Emily|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/16/814929294/covid-19-has-caused-a-shortage-of-face-masks-but-theyre-surprisingly-hard-to-mak|title=COVID-19 Has Caused A Shortage Of Face Masks. But They're Surprisingly Hard To Make|date=March 16, 2020|newspaper=[[NPR]]|accessdate=|authorlink=}}</ref> The corresponding face mask used in the [[European Union]] is the [[FFP mask|FFP2 respirator]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://multimedia.3m.com/mws/media/1791500O/comparison-ffp2-kn95-n95-filtering-facepiece-respirator-classes-tb.pdf|title=Comparison of FFP2, KN95, and N95 and Other Filtering Facepiece Respirator Classes|last=|first=|date=2020-01-01|website=3M Technical Data Bulletin|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/respirators-strategy/crisis-alternate-strategies.html|title=Strategies for Optimizing the Supply of N95 Respirators: Crisis/Alternate Strategies|last=|first=|date=2020-03-17|website=U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n== Recommendations ==\nHealth organizations have recommended that people cover their mouth and nose with a bent elbow or a tissue when coughing or sneezing, and dispose of any tissue immediately.<ref name=\"WHO-advice\" /><ref name=\"AutoDW-55\" /> Surgical masks are recommended for those who may be infected,<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\"who-mask-advices\" /> as wearing a mask can limit the volume and travel distance of [[Respiratory droplet|expiratory droplets]] dispersed when talking, sneezing, and coughing.<ref name=\"nCoV: What the Public Should Do\" /> The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) has issued instructions on when and how to use masks.<ref name=\"WHO masks\" />\n\nMasks have also been recommended for use by those who are taking care of someone who may have the disease.<ref name=\"who-mask-advices\" /> The WHO has recommended the wearing of masks by healthy people only if they are at high risk, such as those who are caring for a person with COVID-19, though they also acknowledge that wearing masks may help people avoid touching their face.<ref name=\"who-mask-advices\" /> Several countries have started to encourage the use of face masks by members of the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cnnespanol.cnn.com/2020/04/01/puede-que-asia-haya-tenido-razon-sobre-el-coronavirus-y-las-mascaras-faciales/ |title=Puede que Asia haya tenido raz\u00f3n sobre el coronavirus y las mascarillas, y el resto del mundo se est\u00e1 convenciendo de ello |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== World Health Organization ===\nWorld Health Organization advice to the public in the context of COVID-19 endorsed the use of masks only under the following conditions:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/when-and-how-to-use-masks|title=Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) advice for the public: When and how to use masks|year=2020|website=World Health Organization|publisher=World Health Organization|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>{{quote frame|\n* If you are healthy, you only need to wear a mask if you are taking care of a person with suspected 2019-nCoV infection.\n* Wear a mask if you are coughing or sneezing.\n* Masks are effective only when used in combination with frequent hand-cleaning with alcohol-based [[hand sanitizer]] or soap and water.\n* If you wear a mask, then you must know how to use it and dispose of it properly.\n|author= World Health Organization\n}}\n\n=== US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention ===\n[[File:Use of Cloth Face Coverings to Help Slow the Spread of COVID-19.pdf|thumb|Guidance from the US [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] on using and making cloth masks during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]<ref name=\"cdc_cloth\"/>]]\nThe [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|United States Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) recommended in April 2020 that the general public wear cloth face coverings in public settings where other [[social distancing]] measures are difficult to maintain, such as grocery stores and pharmacies, especially in areas of significant community-based transmission, due to the significance of [[Asymptomatic carrier|asymptomatic]] and pre-symptomatic disease transmission.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/diy-cloth-face-coverings.html|title=Use of Cloth Face Coverings to Help Slow the Spread of COVID-19|last=|first=|date=2020-04-04|website=U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}} {{PD-inline}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/cloth-face-cover.html|title=Recommendation Regarding the Use of Cloth Face Coverings, Especially in Areas of Significant Community-Based Transmission|last=|first=|date=2020-04-03|website=U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, the CDC recommended that if neither respirators nor surgical masks are available, as a last resort, it may be necessary for healthcare workers to use masks that have never been evaluated or approved by NIOSH or homemade masks, though caution should be exercised when considering this option.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/respirators-strategy/crisis-alternate-strategies.html|title=Strategies for Optimizing the Supply of N95 Respirators: Crisis/Alternate Strategies|last=|first=|date=2020-03-17|website=U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}} {{PD-inline}}</ref> \n\nIn March and April 2020, the CDC faced backlash over their earlier statements advising that most healthy people did not need to wear a mask. The earlier recommendations had been made to try to conserve supplies for medical professionals, but damaged the agency's credibility.<ref name=\"BackfiredNYT\">{{cite news |last1=Tufekci |first1=Zeynep |title=Why Telling People They Don't Need Masks Backfired |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/opinion/coronavirus-face-masks.html |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NPRMasks\">{{cite news |last1=Jingnan |first1=Huo |last2=Aubrey |first2=Allison |last3=Worth |first3=Carmel |title=Should We All Be Wearing Masks In Public? Health Experts Revisit The Question |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/03/31/824560471/should-we-all-be-wearing-masks-in-public-health-experts-revisit-the-question |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=[[NPR]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Prospect\">{{cite news |last1=Dayen |first1=David |title=Mind the Trust Gap |url=https://prospect.org/power/mind-the-trust-gap-coronavirus-government-fail/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=[[The American Prospect]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== China and Asia ===\n[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]] has specifically recommended the use of disposable [[surgical mask|non-surgical medical masks]] by healthy members of the public,<ref name=\"nhc_masks\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> particularly when coming into close contact ({{convert|1|m|ft|0}} or less) with other people.<ref name=\"sci_masks\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nhc.gov.cn/jkj/s3577/202003/0a472cc09e744144883db6a74fe6e760.shtml |title=\u5173\u4e8e\u5370\u53d1\u516c\u4f17\u79d1\u5b66\u6234\u53e3\u7f69\u6307\u5f15\u7684\u901a\u77e5\u5f15 |language=zh |date=18 March 2020 |work=NHC.gov.cn |publisher=[[Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention]] |archiveurl=http://archive.is/mRT0n |archivedate=20 March 2020 }}</ref> [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] recommends wearing a surgical mask when taking public transport or in crowded places.<ref name=\"chp_hk\" /><ref name=\"time5799964\" /> [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Thailand|Thailand]]'s health officials are encouraging people to make cloth face masks at home and wash them daily.<ref name=\"0azBR\" />\n\nWhen asked about the mistakes that other countries were making in the pandemic in March, the [[Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention]] director-general [[George Fu Gao]] said: <blockquote>\"The big mistake in the U.S. and Europe, in my opinion, is that people aren't wearing masks. This virus is transmitted by droplets and close contact. Droplets play a very important role \u2212 you've got to wear a mask, because when you speak, there are always droplets coming out of your mouth. Many people have [[asymptomatic]] or presymptomatic infections. If they are wearing face masks, it can prevent droplets that carry the virus from escaping and infecting others.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cohen |first1=Jon |title=Not wearing masks to protect against coronavirus is a \u2018big mistake,\u2019 top Chinese scientist says |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/not-wearing-masks-protect-against-coronavirus-big-mistake-top-chinese-scientist-says |website=Science |date=27 March 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Rationale for wearing masks ==\n[[File:Watson queue for face masks 20200130 DSCF2199 (49464278376).jpg|thumb|Queue to buy face masks in Hong Kong, January 30, 2020. Everyone in the line is already wearing a disposable medical mask.]]\n\nAmong the reasons cited by Chinese health officials for the wearing of masks, even by healthy individuals, are the following:\n\n# Asymptomatic transmission. Many people can be infected without symptoms or only with mild symptoms.<ref name=\"nhc_why\"/>\n# Impossibility of appropriate social distancing in many public places at all times.<ref name=\"nhc_why\"/>\n# Cost-benefit mismatch. If only the infected individuals wear a mask, they would possibly have a negative incentive to do so. An infected individual might get nothing positive, but only bear the costs such as inconvenience, purchasing expenses, and even prejudice.<ref name=\"nhc_why\"/>\n# There is no shortage of masks in China, which has been producing 100 million masks per day since early March.<ref name=\"nhc_why\"/>\n\nLeading microbiologist [[Yuen Kwok-yung]] from the [[University of Hong Kong]] cites a large [[viral load]] in [[sputum]] and [[saliva]] of an infected person and asymptomatic cases as the reasons why even healthy individuals should wear a mask.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Li|first1=Isabelle|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/exclusive-qa-with-hong-kong-microbiologist-yuen-kwok-yung-who-helped-confirm|title=Q&A with HK microbiologist Yuen Kwok-yung who helped confirm coronavirus' human spread|date=March 10, 2020|work=[[The Straits Times]]|last2=Zuoyan|first2=Zhao}}</ref><ref name=\"hku_saliva\"/>\n\nAccording to Stephen Griffin, a virologist at the [[University of Leeds]], \"Wearing a mask can reduce the propensity [of] people to touch their faces, which is a major source of infection without proper hand hygiene.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/future/article/20200317-how-to-stop-touching-your-face|title=How to avoid touching your face so much|date=18 March 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> The [[precautionary principle]] has also been cited by the ''[[British Medical Journal]]'' as a reason some may encourage universal face mask wearing.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Greenhalgh |first1=Trisha |last2=Schmid |first2=Manuel B |last3=Czypionka |first3=Thomas |last4=Bassler |first4=Dirk |last5=Gruer |first5=Laurence |title=Face masks for the public during the covid-19 crisis |journal=BMJ |date=9 April 2020 |pages=m1435 |doi=10.1136/bmj.m1435 |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/369/bmj.m1435.short |accessdate=27 April 2020 |issn=1756-1833}}</ref>\n\nAsian health officials and experts have been promoting universal masking. For instance, Linfa Wang (a leading infectious disease expert who heads a joint [[Duke University]] and [[National University of Singapore]] research team) stated that masking is about \"preventing the [[Transmission (medicine)|spread of disease]] rather than preventing [[Infection|getting the disease]],\" remarking that the point is to cover the faces of people who are infected but do not know it, so it is imperative for everyone to wear one in public.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Winn |first1=Patrick |title=Will the US ever mimic Asia\u2019s culture of \u2018universal masking\u2019? |url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2020-04-01/will-us-ever-mimic-asia-s-culture-universal-masking |website=Public Radio International |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Shortages of face masks ==\n{{See also|Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n=== Early epidemic in China ===\n[[File:Citizens of Wuhan lining up outside of a drug store to buy masks during the Wuhan coronavirus outbreak.jpg|thumb|People in [[Wuhan]] lining up in front of a drug store to buy [[surgical masks]].]]\n[[File:Surgical mask and 84 disinfectant liquid purchase limit notice at a CSF Market (20200202155633).jpg|thumb|A notice at a supermarket in [[Beijing]], which says each person can only buy one pack of surgical masks and one bottle of 84 disinfectant liquid a day.]]\n[[File:A bag of face masks made by BYD, 2020-04-26.jpg|thumb|Chinese electronics manufacturers, such as [[BYD Electronic]], began to produce surgical masks after the outbreak.]]\n\nAs the epidemic accelerated, the mainland market in China saw a shortage of [[Surgical mask|face masks]] due to increased public demand.<ref name=sohu161795>{{cite news|author=\u8c22\u658c \u5f20\u7eaf|url=http://www.sohu.com/a/368299105_161795|title=\u4e00\u7f69\u96be\u6c42\uff1a\u5357\u90fd\u6c11\u8c03\u5b9e\u6d4b\u8d70\u8bbf\u53d1\u73b0\uff0c\u7ebf\u4e0a\u7ebf\u4e0b\u53e3\u7f69\u57fa\u672c\u5356\u8131\u9500|date=21 January 2020|accessdate=21 January 2020|agency=\u5357\u65b9\u90fd\u5e02\u62a5}}</ref> In Shanghai, customers had to queue for nearly an hour to buy a pack of face masks; stocks were sold out in another in half an hour.<ref name=udn4304194>{{cite news|author1=\u5f90\u6986\u6db5|url=https://money.udn.com/money/story/5648/4304194|title=\u5168\u7403\u5404\u5730\u760b\u6436\u53e3\u7f69 \u5c08\u5bb6\uff1a\u4e0d\u5fc5\u8cb7N95|date=23 January 2020|accessdate=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125103023/https://money.udn.com/money/story/5648/4304194|archive-date=25 January 2020|publisher=\u806f\u5408\u5831|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Hoarding]] and price gouging drove up prices, so the market regulator said it would crack down on such acts.<ref name=southcn190111854>{{cite news|author=\u5218\u704f|url=http://economy.southcn.com/e/2020-01/21/content_190111854.htm|title=\u5e7f\u4e1c\u5e02\u573a\u76d1\u7ba1\u90e8\u95e8\uff1a\u5c06\u575a\u51b3\u6253\u51fb\u56e4\u79ef\u5c45\u5947\u3001\u54c4\u62ac\u4ef7\u683c\u7b49\u884c\u4e3a|date=21 January 2020|accessdate=21 January 2020|agency=\u5357\u65b9\u7f51}}</ref><ref name=gov1620613>{{cite web|url=http://scjgj.beijing.gov.cn/zwxx/ttgg/202001/t20200122_1620613.html|title=\u5e02\u573a\u4ef7\u683c\u884c\u4e3a\u63d0\u9192\u4e66|date=n.d.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127080911/http://scjgj.beijing.gov.cn/zwxx/ttgg/202001/t20200122_1620613.html|archive-date=27 January 2020|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2020, price controls were imposed on all face masks on [[Taobao]] and [[Tmall]].<ref name=ycwb30486944>{{cite news|author=\u9648\u6cfd\u4e91|url=http://news.ycwb.com/2020-01/22/content_30486944.htm|title=\u53e3\u7f69\u4e70\u4e0d\u5230\u600e\u4e48\u529e\uff1f\u8fd9\u4e9b\u836f\u5e97\u5e73\u53f0\u6625\u8282\u671f\u95f4\u6301\u7eed\u4f9b\u5e94|date=22 January 2020|accessdate=22 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122102833/http://news.ycwb.com/2020-01/22/content_30486944.htm|archive-date=22 January 2020|agency=\u91d1\u7f8a\u7f51|url-status=live}}</ref> Other Chinese e-commerce platforms \u2013 [[JD.com]],<ref name=bjnews677805>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677805.html|title=\u4eac\u4e1c\uff1a\u7981\u6b62\u7b2c\u4e09\u65b9\u5546\u5bb6\u53e3\u7f69\u6da8\u4ef7|author=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5|date=22 January 2020|website=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127082917/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677805.html|archive-date=27 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Suning.com]],<ref name=bjnews677740>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677740.html|title=\u82cf\u5b81\u6613\u8d2d\uff1a\u53e3\u7f69\u7b49\u5065\u5eb7\u7c7b\u5546\u54c1\u7981\u6da8\u4ef7\uff0c\u5e76\u5f00\u5c55\u767e\u4ebf\u8865\u8d34|author=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5|date=22 January 2020|website=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122023040/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677740.html|archive-date=22 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Pinduoduo]]<ref name=bjnews677744>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677744.html|title=\u62fc\u591a\u591a\uff1a\u5bf9\u53e3\u7f69\u7b49\u4ea7\u54c1\u8fdb\u884c\u76d1\u6d4b\uff0c\u6076\u610f\u6da8\u4ef7\u8005\u5c06\u4e0b\u67b6|author=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5|date=22 January 2020|website=\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122023043/http://www.bjnews.com.cn/finance/2020/01/22/677744.html|archive-date=22 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \u2013 did likewise; third-party vendors would be subject to price caps, with violators subject to sanctions.\n\nBy March China had quadrupled its production capacity (100 million masks per day).<ref name=\"nhc_why\"/>\n\n=== National stocks and shortages ===\nIn 2006, 156 million masks were added to the US [[Strategic National Stockpile]] in anticipation of a flu pandemic.<ref name=\"Manjoo\" /> After they were used against the [[2009 flu pandemic]], neither the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] nor the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]] renewed the stocks.<ref name=\"Manjoo\" /> By 1 April, the US's [[Strategic National Stockpile]] was nearly emptied.<ref name=\"washingtonpost7148009252\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-protective-gear-stockpile-depleted/2020/04/01/44d6592a-741f-11ea-ae50-7148009252e3_story.html|title=Protective gear in national stockpile is nearly depleted, DHS officials say|last=enforcement|first=Nick Miroff closeNick MiroffReporter covering immigration|last2=Homel|first2=the Department of|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401225900/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-protective-gear-stockpile-depleted/2020/04/01/44d6592a-741f-11ea-ae50-7148009252e3_story.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020|last3=SecurityEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollow}}</ref>{{clarify|date=April 2020}} \n\nIn France, [[2009 swine flu pandemic|2009 H1N1]]-related spending rose to \u20ac382 million, mainly on supplies and vaccines, which was later criticised.<ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=\":20\" /> It was decided in 2011 to not replenesh its stocks and rely more on supply from China and [[Just-in-time manufacturing|just-in-time logistics]].<ref name=\":19\" /> In 2010, its stock included 1&nbsp;billion surgical masks and 600 million FFP2 masks; in early 2020 it was 150 millions and zero, respectively.<ref name=\":19\" /> While stocks were progressively reduced, a 2013 rationale stated the aim to reduce costs of acquisition and storage, now distributing this effort to all private enterprises as an optional best practice to ensure their workers' protection.<ref name=\":19\" /> This was especially relevant to FFP2 masks, more costly to acquire and store.<ref name=\":19\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/sciences/quand-l-etat-stratege-a-renonce-a-renouveler-ses-stocks-de-masques-20200319|title=Quand l'\u00c9tat strat\u00e8ge a renonc\u00e9 \u00e0 renouveler ses stocks de masques|last=Roy|first=Soline|last2=Barotte|first2=Nicolas|date=19 March 2020|website=Le Figaro.fr|language=fr|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> As the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]] took an increasing toll on medical supplies, masks and PPE supplies ran low, causing national outrage. France needs 40 millions masks per week, according to French president [[Emmanuel Macron]].<ref name=\":25\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rfi.fr/en/international/20200331-macron-40-million-masks-covid-19|title=France to produce 40 million face masks by end of April for domestic battle against Covid-19|date=31 March 2020|publisher=Radio France Internationale|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> France instructed its few remaining mask-producing factories to work 24/7 shifts, and to ramp up national production to 40 million masks per month.<ref name=\":25\" /> French lawmakers opened an inquiry on the past management of these strategic stocks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rfi.fr/en/france/20200401-where-billion-masks-french-coronavirus-committee-asks|title=Covid-19: French lawmakers to investigate where one and a half billion masks sent|date=1 April 2020|publisher=Radio France Internationale|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> The mask shortage has been called a ''\"scandal d'\u00c9tat\"'' (State scandal).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.franceinter.fr/societe/penurie-de-masques-les-raisons-d-un-scandale-d-etat |title=P\u00e9nurie de masques : les raisons d'un \"scandale d'\u00c9tat\" |publisher=Franceinter.fr |date=n.d.|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn late-March/early-April 2020, as Western countries were in turn dependent on China for supplies of masks and other equipment, China was seen as making soft-power play to influence world opinion.<ref name=bbc52092395/><ref name=20200402businessinsider/> However, a batch of masks purchased by the Netherlands was reportedly rejected as being sub-standard. The Dutch health ministry issued a recall of 600,000 face masks from a Chinese supplier on 21 March which did not fit properly and whose filters did not work as intended despite them having a quality certificate.<ref name=\"bbc52092395\"/><ref name=\"20200402businessinsider\"/> The Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs responded that the customer should \"double-check the instructions to make sure that you ordered, paid for and distributed the right ones. Do not use non-surgical masks for surgical purposes\".<ref name=20200402businessinsider/>\n\n===N95 and FFP masks===\n[[File:Wearing FFP mask during the COVID-19 pandemic in Khmelnytskyi, April 2020.jpg|thumb|upright|A woman in Ukraine wearing an FFP mask after masking in public places was made mandatory.]]\nN95 and FFP masks were in short supply and high demand during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Johnson|first=Marty|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/public-global-health/489782-feds-have-15-million-expired-n95-masks-in-storage|title=Feds have 1.5 million expired N95 masks in storage despite CDC clearing them for use on COVID-19: report|date=March 26, 2020|work=The Hill|access-date=April 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":19\" /> Production of N95 masks was limited due to constraints on the supply of [[nonwoven polypropylene]] fabric (which is used as the primary filter), as well as the cessation of exports from China.<ref name=\"VOADeliver\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Evan|first1=Melanie|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-pressures-supply-chain-for-protective-masks-11583552527|title=Critical Component of Protective Masks in Short Supply - The epidemic has driven up demand for material in N95 filters; 'everyone thinks there is this magic factory somewhere'|date=March 7, 2020|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=|last2=Hufford|first2=Austen|authorlink=}}</ref> China controls 50{{nbsp}}percent of global production of masks, and facing its own coronavirus epidemic, dedicated all its production for domestic use, only allowing exports through government-allocated humanitarian assistance.<ref name=\"VOADeliver\" />\n\nIn March 2020, US President [[Donald Trump]] applied the [[Defense Production Act]] against the American company [[3M]], which allows the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] to obtain N95 respirators from 3M.<ref name=\"Fabian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-02/trump-says-he-ll-use-production-act-to-supply-ventilator-makers|title=Trump Attacks 3M Over Mask Production, Drawing Company Pushback|last1=Fabian|first1=Jordan|last2=Clough|first2=Rick|date=2 April 2020|website=Bloomberg}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Whalen|first1=Jeanne|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/inside-americas-mask-crunch-a-slow-government-reaction-and-an-industry-wary-of-liability/2020/04/02/b3155e2a-6f85-11ea-aa80-c2470c6b2034_story.html|title=Inside Americas Mask Crunch|date=3 April 2020|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|last2=Helderman|first2=Rosalind S.|last3=Hamburger|first3=Tom}}</ref> [[White House]] trade adviser [[Peter Navarro]] stated that there were concerns that 3M products were not making their way to the US.<ref name=\"Fabian\" /> 3M replied that it has not changed the prices it charges, and was unable to control the prices its dealers or retailers charge.<ref name=\"Fabian\" />\n\nIn early April 2020, Berlin politician [[Andreas Geisel]] alleged that a shipment of 200,000 N95 masks that it had ordered from American producer 3M's China facility were intercepted in [[Bangkok]] and diverted to the United States. [[Berlin Police|Berlin police]] president [[:de:Barbara Slowik|Barbara Slowik]] stated that she believed \"this is related to the US government's export ban.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/wissen/usa-fangen-200-000-schutzmasken-ab-berlins-innensenator-spricht-von-moderner-piraterie/25712976.html |title=Berlins Innensenator spricht von \"moderner Piraterie\" |first1=Julius |last1=Betschka |first2=Alexander |last2=Fr\u00f6hlich |date=3 April 2020 |newspaper=[[Der Tagesspiegel]] |language=de}}</ref> 3M said they had no knowledge of the shipment, stating \"We know nothing of an order from the Berlin police for 3M masks that come from China,\" and the US government denied that any confiscation had taken place and said that they use appropriate channels for all their purchases.<ref name=Betschka>{{cite news |url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/wissen/usa-fangen-200-000-schutzmasken-ab-berlins-innensenator-spricht-von-moderner-piraterie/25712976.html |title=Berlins Innensenator spricht von \"moderner Piraterie\" |first1=Julius |last1=Betschka |first2=Alexander |last2=Fr\u00f6hlich |date=3 April 2020 |newspaper=[[Der Tagesspiegel]] |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |title=Schutzmasken konfisziert? Schwere Vorw\u00fcrfe aus Berlin: Jetzt reagiert das Wei\u00dfe Haus |newspaper=[[t-online.de]]|date=April 4, 2020 |url= https://www.t-online.de/nachrichten/ausland/id_87648648/coronavirus-mundschutz-konfisziert-usa-reagiert-auf-vorwuerfe-aus-berlin.html |accessdate=}}</ref> Berlin police later confirmed that the shipment was not seized by US authorities, but was said to have simply been bought at a better price, widely believed to be from a German dealer or China. This revelation outraged the Berlin opposition, whose [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|CDU]] parliamentary group leader Burkard Dregger accused Geisel of \"deliberately misleading Berliners\" in order \"to cover up its own inability to obtain protective equipment\". [[Free Democratic Party (Germany)|FDP]] interior expert Marcel Luthe said \"Big names in international politics like Berlin's senator Geisel are blaming others and telling US piracy to serve anti-American clich\u00e9s.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=&sl=auto&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.tagesspiegel.de%2Fberlin%2F200-000-atemschutzmasken-doch-nicht-konfisziert-lieferung-fuer-berliner-polizei-wurde-in-thailand-zu-besserem-preis-aufgekauft%2F25715448.html&sandbox=1 |title=200,000 respirators not confiscated: Delivery for Berlin police was bought in Thailand at a better price|first=Alexander|last=Fr\u00f6hlich|date=4 April 2020 |newspaper=[[Der Tagesspiegel]]|language=english}}</ref> ''[[Politico Europe]]'' reported that \"the Berliners are taking a page straight out of the Trump playbook and not letting facts get in the way of a good story.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/berlin-lets-mask-slip-on-feelings-for-trumps-america/|title=Berlin lets mask slip on feelings for Trump's America|date=April 10, 2020|newspaper=[[Politico Europe]]}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' also reported that \"There is no solid proof Trump [nor any other American official] approved the [German] heist\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/12/us-global-reputation-rock-bottom-donald-trump-coronavirus|title=US's global reputation hits rock-bottom over Trump's coronavirus response|first1=Simon|last1=Tisdall|date=12 April 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Jared Moskowitz]], head of the [[Florida Division of Emergency Management]], accused 3M of selling N95 masks directly to foreign countries for cash, instead of the US. Moskowitz stated that 3M agreed to authorized distributors and brokers to represent they were selling the masks to [[Florida]], but instead his team for the last several weeks \"get to warehouses that are completely empty.\" He then said the 3M-authorized US distributors later told him the masks Florida contracted for never showed up because the company instead prioritized orders that came in later, for higher prices, from foreign countries (including Germany, Russia, and France). As a result, Moskowitz highlighted the issue on Twitter, saying he decided to \u201ctroll\u201d 3M.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Halon|first=Yael|url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/florida-emergency-official-3m-selling-masks-overseas|title=Florida emergency management official says 3M selling masks to foreign countries: 'We're chasing ghosts'|date=April 3, 2020|work=Fox News|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://miami.cbslocal.com/video/4503117-interview-with-jared-moskowitz-director-of-floridas-division-of-emergency-management/|title=Interview With Jared Moskowitz, Director of Florida's Division of Emergency Management|date=April 3, 2020|work=WFOR-TV|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Man|first=Anthony|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/coronavirus/fl-ne-ventilators-icu-beds-florida-coronavirus-hurricane-season-20200405-4qn46bbq4zfazo5bqapggodftu-story.html|title=Florida emergency management chief says state will have enough ICU beds and ventilators|date=5 April 2020|work=Sun-Sentinel|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> ''[[Forbes]]'' reported that \"roughly 280 million masks from warehouses around the US had been purchased by foreign buyers [on March 30, 2020] and were earmarked to leave the country, according to the broker \u2014 and that was in ''one'' day\", causing massive critical shortages of masks in the US.<ref>{{Cite news|last=DiSalvo|first=David|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2020/03/30/i-spent-a-day-in-the-coronavirus-driven-feeding-frenzy-of-n95-mask-sellers-and-buyers-and-this-is-what-i-learned/#c690bff56d44|title=I Spent A Day In The Coronavirus-Driven Feeding Frenzy Of N95 Mask Sellers And Buyers And This Is What I Learned|date=30 March 2020|work=Forbes|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|authors=Natasha Bertrand, Gabby Orr, Daneil Lippman and Nahal Toosi|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/31/pence-task-force-coronavirus-aid-157806|title=Pence task force freezes coronavirus aid amid backlash|date=31 March 2020|work=Politico|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs more and more countries restricted the export of N95 masks, Novo Textiles in [[British Columbia]] had plans to become the number-one manufacturer in [[Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/covid-19-coquitlam-company-retools-will-be-first-in-canada-to-produce-n95-respirators/|title=COVID-19: Coquitlam company retools, will be first in Canada to produce N95 respirators|date=2020-04-06|language=en|publication-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> AMD Medicom in [[Quebec]] also plans to become the second Canadian manufacturer of N95 masks, with a contract to supply the [[Government of Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/article-quebec-mask-maker-amd-medicom-launching-canadian-manufacturing/#_=_|title=Medicom to begin manufacturing N95 masks in Canada as foreign countries curb exports|date=2020-04-05|language=en|publication-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n===Attitudes===\nIn [[East Asian]] societies, a primary reason for mask-wearing is to protect others from oneself.<ref name=nyt-mwi>{{cite web |last1=Onishi |first1=Norimitsu |last2=M\u00e9heut |first2=Constant |title=Mask-Wearing Is a Very New Fashion in Paris (and a Lot of Other Places) |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/world/europe/virus-mask-wearing.html |website=The New York Times |date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=wo-wsc>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Tessa |title=Why some countries wear face masks and others don't |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-52015486 |website=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref> It is seen as a collective responsibility to reduce the transmission of the virus.<ref name=zh-fmc>{{cite web |last1=Zheng |first1=Sarah |title=Face mask culture during the coronavirus: East vs West |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3075211/face-masks-and-coronavirus-how-culture-affects-your-decision |website=South China Morning Post |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The broad assumption behind the act is that anyone, including seemingly healthy people, can be a carrier of the coronavirus.<ref name=wo-wsc/> A face mask is thus seen as a symbol of solidarity.<ref name=zh-fmc/> Elsewhere, the need for mask-wearing is often seen in an individual's perspective where masks only serve to protect oneself.<ref name=nyt-mwi/> \n\nCultural norms and social pressure may also impede mask-wearing in public.<ref name=le-wfm>{{cite web |last1=Leung |first1=Hillary |title=Why Face Masks Are Encouraged in Asia, but Shunned in the U.S. |url=https://time.com/5799964/coronavirus-face-mask-asia-us/ |website=Time |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> According to the Hong Kong doctor and infectious disease expert Joseph Tsang, the promotion of universal masking may resolve perceptions against mask-wearing, because mask-wearing is intimidating if few people wear masks due to cultural barriers, but if all people wear masks it shows a message that people are in this together.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Winn |first1=Patrick |title=Will the US ever mimic Asia\u2019s culture of \u2018universal masking\u2019? |url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2020-04-01/will-us-ever-mimic-asia-s-culture-universal-masking |website=Public Radio International |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the western world, the public usage of masks still often carries a large stigma,<ref name=nyt-mwi/><ref name=zh-fmc/><ref name=te-wwm/> as it is seen as a sign of sickness.<ref name=te-wwm>{{cite web |last1=Tett |first1=Gillian |title=Why wearing masks may be the way forward |url=https://www.ft.com/content/d7057a2e-739d-11ea-95fe-fcd274e920ca |website=Financial Times |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> This stigmatization is a large obstacle to overcome, because people may feel too ashamed to wear a mask in public and therefore opt to not wear one.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Friedman |first1=Uri |title=Face Masks Are In |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/04/america-asia-face-mask-coronavirus/609283/ |website=The Atlantic |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Secondly, it is heavily racialized as an Asian phenomenon.<ref name=zh-fmc/> However, there is also a divide within the western world, as seen in the [[Czech Republic]] and [[Slovakia]] where mass mobilization has occurred to reinforce the solidarity in mask-wearing since March 2020.<ref name=nyt-mwi/> \n\nOn social media, there has been an effort with the #masks4all campaign to encourage people to use masks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: To Mask Or Not To Mask? #Masks4All Seeks Everyone To Cover Their Mouths |url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2020/03/31/coronavirus-to-mask-or-not-to-mask-masks4all-seeks-everyone-to-cover-their-mouths/ | website=CBS New York| |date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Mask-wearing has been called a [[prosocial behavior]] in which one protects others within their community.<ref name=hj-wapo>{{cite web |last1=Howard |first1=Jeremy |title=Simple DIY masks could help flatten the curve. We should all wear them in public. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2020/03/28/masks-all-coronavirus/ |website=Washington Post |date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New local website aims to promote mask wearing to help flatten the curve |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/new-local-website-aims-to-promote-mask-wearing-to-help-flatten-the-curve-20200407 |website=News24 |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Fashion===\nFace masks have had an impact on fashion, with the masks themselves becoming a fashion statements, [[haute couture]] brands having pivoted to address both [[public health]] and aesthetic needs.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Friedman|first=Vanessa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/style/face-mask-coronavirus.html|title=Fashion and Masks in the Age of Coronavirus|date=March 17, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 18,  2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Hine|first=Samuel|url=https://www.gq.com/story/streetwear-face-mask-coronavirus|title=The Streetwear Face Mask Market Is Booming|date=April 3, 2020|work=GQ|access-date=April 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sanoff|first=Rachel|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/07/coronavirus-face-mask-fashion|title=Coronavirus couture: the rise of the $60 designer face mask|date=April 7, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=April 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Petrarca|first=Emilia|url=https://www.thecut.com/2020/04/the-aesthetics-of-face-masks-in-the-age-of-coronavirus.html|title=What Does Your Face Mask Say About You?|date=April 10, 2020|work=The Cut|access-date=April 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Mask use and policies by country and territory ==\n{{See also|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:02.05 \u7e3d\u7d71\u8a2a\u8996\u300c\u53f0\u7063\u5eb7\u5320\u88fd\u9020\u516c\u53f8\u300d (49491845167).jpg|thumb|The government of Taiwan instituted a mask rationing system. With population of 24 million, Taiwan has been producing more than 10 million masks per day since March.]]\n[[File:Pentalingual notice of subway mask policy at L2 Dongzhimen Station (20200421163057).jpg|thumb|[[Beijing Subway]] advises passengers to wear masks when taking trains]]\n\n* {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Argentina|Argentina]]: After appearance of three asymptomatic cases, the capital [[Buenos Aires]] introduced compulsory masking since April 14. Wearing a mask was made obligatory for everyone on public transit and everyone who contacts with the public in their position. Violators can face a fine. Authorities also prohibited the sale of N95 face masks to non-medical workers, suggesting the general public to use home-made masks instead.<ref name=\"ar200414\">{{cite news |url=https://santiagotimes.cl/2020/04/14/covid-19-face-masks-mandatory-in-buenos-aires-as-of-next-wednesday |title=COVID-19: Face masks mandatory in Buenos Aires as of next Wednesday |work=The Santiago Times |date=14 April 2020 }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Austria}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Austria|Austria]]: Everyone entering a supermarket, a grocery store, or a drug store must wear a face mask.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-52126735 Coronavirus: Expert panel to assess face mask use by public], BBC News, David Shukman, 1{{nbsp}}April 2020.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bell|first=Bethany|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-52143873|title=Coronavirus: Why you now have to wear a mask in Austrian shops|date=April 6, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Bahamas}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bahamas|Bahamas]]: On April 19, the prime minister announced that wearing a mask or covering one's face with clothing is mandatory in public. Employers must provide their employees who are serving the general public with masks.<ref name=\"bs200419\">{{cite news |url=http://eleutheranews.com/?p=22315 |title=Bahamas PM\u2019s National Press Conference: Update on COVID-19 Response |work=Eleutheran Newspaper |date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n*{{Flagicon|Bahrain}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bahrain|Bahrain]]: The Kingdom made wearing face masks in public areas compulsory for citizens and residents as well as shop workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arab.news/8unvt|title=Bahrain makes face masks compulsory in public, allows shops to re-open|date=2020-04-09|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Benin}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Benin|Benin]]: From April 8, Benin's authorities began enforcing the mandatory wearing of face masks to halt the coronavirus.<ref>[https://www.barrons.com/news/benin-police-enforce-mask-wearing-in-bid-to-stop-virus-01586363106 Benin Police Enforce Mask Wearing In Bid To Stop Virus],<i>Barron's</i>, 8{{nbsp}}April 2020.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia and Herzegovina]]: Wearing a face mask is compulsory.<ref name=\"newshub\">{{Cite news |last=Andelane |first=Lana |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/world/2020/04/coronavirus-countries-where-face-masks-are-mandatory-in-covid-19-fight.html |title=Coronavirus: Countries where face masks are mandatory in COVID-19 fight |date=April 7, 2020 |work=Newshub |access-date=April 11, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Drew Hinshaw|first=Catherine Lucey|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-reviews-guidance-on-masks-to-fight-coronavirus-as-europe-embraces-their-use-11585676543|title=U.S. Reviews Guidance on Masks to Fight Coronavirus as Europe Embraces Their Use|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Bulgaria}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bulgaria|Bulgaria]]: Bulgaria's government passed an order imposing an obligation to wear face masks on March 30. The order was cancelled the next day and changed into a recommendation, due to legal complaints.<ref>{{cite news |title=European authorities\u2019 shifting advice on face masks adds to confusion in coronavirus crisis|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/04/european-authorities-shifting-advice-on-face-masks-adds-to-confusion-in-coronavirus-crisis-164435|author1=Carmen Paun |author2=Ashleigh Furlong |author3=Politico Europe |author4=Judith Mischke|date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Cambodia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cambodia|Cambodia]]: Many Cambodians started wearing face masks soon after the outbreak began in Wuhan. Businesses started to require customers to wear masks.<ref name=\"cb20200330\">{{cite news |title=Cambodian Businesses Embrace Protective Measures Against Coronavirus |url=https://www.voacambodia.com/a/cambodian-businesses-embrace-protective-measures-against-coronavirus/5352023.html |author1=Phorn Bopha |author2=Sokummono Khan |work=VOA Khmer }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Cameroon}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cameroon|Cameroon]]: On April 6, mayor of [[Douala]] announced that wearing a mask will be mandatory to slow the spread of coronavirus.<ref>[https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/cameroon-city-makes-wearing-mask-mandatory-fight-against Cameroon City Makes Wearing Mask Mandatory in Fight Against Coronavirus],<i>VOA News</i>, 7{{nbsp}}April 2020.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|Canada]]: Since April 6, health officials recommend wearing non-medical masks in situations where physical distancing from others is difficult (like buying groceries, or public transit).<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-tam-offers-new-advice-wear-a-non-medical-mask-when-shopping-or-using/ Theresa Tam offers new advice: Wear a non-medical face mask when shopping or using public transit],<i>The Globe and Mail</i>, 6{{nbsp}}April 2020.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Chile}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Chile|Chile]]: From April 8, Chilean Health Minister announced wearing a mask is mandatory in public transit. <ref>[https://www.diariolibre.com/actualidad/internacional/chile-afirma-estar-en-una-guerra-por-los-recursos-contra-el-covid-19-OJ18118776 Chile afirma estar en una 'guerra' por los recursos contra el COVID-19],<i>Diario Libre</i>, 6{{nbsp}}April 2020.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|China}} [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]]: Healthy individuals are advised to wear disposable medical masks in public places.<ref name=\"nhc_masks\"/><ref name=\"sci_masks\"/> Some local governments require wearing masks when going outside. Shanghai makes wearing masks mandatory in public places. <ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-02/08/c_138766346.htm Shanghai makes wearing masks mandatory in public places],<i>Xinhuanet</i>, 8{{nbsp}}February 2020.</ref>\n*{{Flagicon|Colombia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Colombia|Colombia]]: In response to the most recent recommendations of the WHO, Colombia changed its policy on the use of masks and made it mandatory throughout the country for the use of public transport during the coronavirus emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/colombia/2020/04/06/el-uso-de-mascarillas-se-vuelve-obligatorio-en-todo-colombia/|title=El uso de mascarillas se vuelve obligatorio en todo Colombia|last=|first=|date=|website=Infobae|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Cuba}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cuba|Cuba]]: On March 11, the government urged citizens to make their own masks, while the textile industry was drafted to fabricate them. People were advised to carry several cloth masks with them, depending on how many hours they plan to spend in public areas.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-cuba/update-1-cuba-confirms-first-coronavirus-cases-urges-citizens-to-make-own-masks-idUSL1N2B501N |title=Cuba confirms 1st coronavirus cases, urges citizens to make own masks |date=11 March 2020 |work=Reuters |access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> Later, wearing a mask was made mandatory.<ref>[http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/opinion/-pregnant-phase-for-jamaica_191496?profile=1096 'Pregnant' phase for Jamaica],<i>Jamaica Observer</i>, 6{{nbsp}}April 2020.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Czech Republic}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Czech Republic|Czech Republic]]: Forbidden to go out in public without wearing a mask, or covering one's nose and mouth.<ref name=\"czsk\"/>\n*[[Dominican Republic]]: Since April 16, the use of face mask is mandatory in all public spaces and in the workplace.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listindiario.com/economia/2020/04/16/613491/el-uso-de-mascarillas-en-el-pais-sera-obligatorio-en-espacios-publicos-y-lugares-de-trabajo|title=El uso de mascarillas en el pa\u00eds ser\u00e1 obligatorio en espacios p\u00fablicos y lugares de trabajo|last=Diario|first=Listin|date=2020-04-16|website=listindiario.com|language=ES|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Democratic Republic of the Congo}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Democratic Republic of the Congo|DR Congo]]: Since April 20, wearing masks in the capital of [[Kinshasa]] is mandatory.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Tasamba|first=James|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/covid-19-rwanda-dr-congo-make-mask-wearing-mandatory/1810165|title=Rwanda, DR Congo make mask wearing mandatory|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Ecuador}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ecuador|Ecuador]]: On April 8, the Emergency Operations Committee (COE) decided to make face masks obligatory in public spaces.<ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-04/08/c_138956755.htm LatAm countries turn to face masks to contain pandemic],<i>Xinhuanet</i>, 8{{nbsp}}April 2020.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Ethiopia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ethiopia|Ethiopia]]: The Council of Ministers approved a regulation that outlaws [[handshake]]s, and obligates the use of face masks in public places.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Samuel|first=Gelila|url=https://addisfortune.news/ethiopia-outlaws-handshakes-obliges-masks-in-public-places|title=Ethiopia Outlaws Handshakes, Obliges Masks in Public Places|date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]]: On March 3, the government issued a degree announcing [[requisition]] of stocks of FFP2 and anti-splash masks until May 31, 2020.<ref name=\"frdecree3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000041679951&categorieLien=id |title=D\u00e9cret n\u00b0 2020-190 du 3 mars 2020 relatif aux r\u00e9quisitions n\u00e9cessaires dans le cadre de la lutte contre le virus covid-19 |work=Legifrance |date=3 March 2020 |language=French }}</ref>\n*{{Flagicon|Gabon}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Gabon|Gabon]]: On April 10, the Gabonese government announced individuals in all parts of the country are required to wear masks in public to limit the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ga.usembassy.gov/u-s-citizen-services/coronavirus-update/|title=COVID-19 Information|website=U.S. Embassy in Gabon|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Germany}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany|Germany]]: On March 31, [[Jena]] was the first large German city to introduce an obligation to wear masks, or makeshift masks including scarves, in supermarkets, public transport, and buildings with public traffic.<ref name=\"de_jena\">{{Cite news |last=Chambers |first=Madeline |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-germany-masks/german-city-introduces-face-masks-for-shoppers-as-coronavirus-spreads-idUSKBN21I10K |title=German city introduces face masks for shoppers as coronavirus spreads |date=31 March 2020 |access-date=2 April 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> On April 2, the [[Robert Koch Institute]], the federal epidemic authority, changed its previous recommendation that only people with symptoms should wear masks to also include people without symptoms.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.welt.de/wissenschaft/article206979269/Corona-Robert-Koch-Institut-aendert-Einschaetzung-zu-Mundschutz.html |title=Pl\u00f6tzlich \u00e4ndert das Robert-Koch-Institut seine Einsch\u00e4tzung zum Mundschutz |date=2 April 2020 |work=Die Welt |access-date=2 April 2020 |agency=dpa/AP |language=de}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Guinea}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guinea|Guinea]]: Guinean President Alpha Conde decided to make wearing masks compulsory.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Masilela|first=Brenda|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/africa/guinean-president-makes-masks-compulsory-in-bid-to-curb-the-spread-of-coronavirus-46700614|title=Guinean president makes masks compulsory in bid to curb the spread of coronavirus|date=April 14, 2020}},<i>IOL</i></ref>\n* {{flagicon|Honduras}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Honduras|Honduras]]: From April 7, Honduras President announced all citizens will now be required to cover their mouths when they are outside.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Archeta|first=Kisa|url=https://covid19data.com/2020/04/07/honduras-makes-it-mandatory-to-wear-face-masks-in-public/|title=Honduras makes it mandatory to wear face masks in public|date=April 7, 2020}},<i>COVID-19 World News</i></ref>\n* {{flagicon|Hong Kong}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Hong Kong|Hong Kong]]: Members of the public are recommended 