histan govt makes face masks mandatory],<i>Pakistan Today</i>, 18{{nbsp}}April 2020.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Panama}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Panama|Panama]]: Panama has made it obligatory to wear a face mask whenever going outside, while also recommending the manufacture of a homemade cloth face mask to those who cannot purchase face masks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvn-2.com/nacionales/Coronavirus-en-Panama-obligatorio-usar-mascarilla-salir-casa_0_5550944856.html |title=Es 'obligatorio' usar mascarilla si va a salir de casa, seg\u00fan ministra consejera de Salud |date=7 April 2020 |website=TVN}}</ref>\n*{{Flagicon|Peru}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Peru|Peru]]: From April 7, the Peruvian government started distributing free masks after decreeing their mandatory use in the streets to chase away the new coronavirus, said President [[Martin Vizcarra]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/agencias/2020/04/03/mascarillas-gratis-peru-decreta-su-uso-obligatorio-para-enfrentar-el-coronavirus-3/|title=Mascarillas gratis: Per\u00fa decreta su uso obligatorio para enfrentar el coronavirus|last=Mercado|first=David|date=|website=Infobae|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Philippines}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|Philippines]]: From\u00a02 April, the government\u00a0required\u00a0all those living in areas under enhanced community quarantine to wear face masks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2020/04/02/philippines-requires-people-to-wear-masks-in-public|title=Philippines requires people to wear masks in public|date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Poland}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Poland|Poland]]: Since April 16, covering lips and nose is compulsory before leaving one's house (''e.g.'', by a disposable mask, cloth mask, or scarf).<ref name=\"pl16\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.pl/web/koronawirus/zaslon-usta-i-nos |title=Wychodzisz z domu? Zas\u0142o\u0144 usta i nos! |date=16 April 2020 |work=Gov.pl }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Russia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Russia|Russia]]: Khabarovsk has made the wearing of face masks obligatory to fight the spike in [[respiratory disease]]s and prevent the spread of the coronavirus. <ref>[https://tass.com/society/1117559 Face masks made mandatory in Russia\u2019s Khabarovsk to prevent coronavirus spread],<i>Tass</i>, 7{{nbsp}}April 2020.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Rwanda}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Rwanda|Rwanda]]: On April 20, Cabinet Minister of Health [[Daniel Ngamije]] said the latest guidelines require everyone to wear a mask in public, and at home during the lockdown and thereafter. <ref name=\":0\" />\n* {{flagicon|Scotland}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Scotland|Scotland]]: On April 28, the [[First Minister for Scotland]] [[Nicola Sturgeon]] advised the voluntary use of cloth face masks in enclosed spaces such as shops and public transport (but not generally in public), while noting their limitation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scottish government suggests covering face in shops |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-52457324 |accessdate=28 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Singapore}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore|Singapore]]: Masks have been widely used by healthy individuals despite initial absence of official advice to do so.<ref name=\"20200131straitstimes\" /> General mask-wearing was no longer discouraged from April 3,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/coronavirus-govt-will-no-longer-discourage-wearing-of-masks-to-give-reusable-masks|title=Coronavirus: Singapore Govt will no longer discourage wearing of masks, to give reusable masks to all households|last=|first=|date=2020-04-03|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> and made mandatory outside of one's residence from April 14.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/covid19-wearing-masks-compulsory-lawrence-wong-12640828|title=COVID-19: Compulsory to wear mask when leaving the house, says Lawrence Wong|last=|first=|date=2020-04-14|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Spain}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|Spain]]: the government distributes free face masks for commuters in large transportation hubs, but it is not mandatory to wear them.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spain to hand out free face masks for commuters to help return to work |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/11/spain-hand-face-masks-allow-limited-return-work/ |website=The Telegraph |accessdate=21 April 2020 |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Slovakia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Slovakia|Slovakia]]: Forbidden to go out in public without wearing a mask or covering one's nose and mouth.<ref name=\"czsk\"/><ref name=\"newshub\" />\n* {{flagicon|Slovenia}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Slovenia|Slovenia]]: From March 29, wearing a face mask, even one made at home, or equivalents such as scarves that cover the mouth and nose is mandatory along with protective gloves; the decree stipulates that masks and gloves need to be worn in indoor public spaces.<ref>[https://www.total-slovenia-news.com/politics/5951-covid-19-slovenia COVID-19 & Slovenia, Night 29 March: Movement Restrictions, Mandatory Masks, More Aid for Individuals],<i>Total Slovenia News</i>, 29{{nbsp}}March 2020.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|South Africa}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa|South Africa]]: On 10 April, Minister of Health recommended that the general public use cloth face masks when going out in public (in addition to hand-washing and social distancing).<ref name=\"gov.za2003\" /><ref name=\"sac-masks\">{{Cite web|url=https://sacoronavirus.co.za/2020/04/10/everyone-should-wear-a-face-mask/|title=Everyone should wear a face mask|date=2020-04-10|website=COVID-19 South African online portal|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> After May 1, covering one's nose and mouth will be mandatory in public (with a cloth mask, scarf, T-shirt, etc.).<ref name=\"cna_sa\">{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/south-africans-must-wear-masks-after-covid-19-lockdown-eases-12677094 |title=South Africans must wear masks after COVID-19 lockdown eases: Minister |date=25 Apr 2020 |work=CNA }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|South Korea}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]]: Masks have been widely used by healthy individuals despite absence of official advice to do so.<ref name=\"hzpH7\" /> The government implemented a policy of centralized procurement and rationing of face masks, purchasing 80 percent of national production since early March.<ref name=\"nyt_kor\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/opinion/covid-face-mask-shortage.html |title=How South Korea Solved Its Face Mask Shortage |date=April 1, 2020 |first=E. Tammy |last=Kim |work=New York Times }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Taiwan}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan|Taiwan]]: On January 21, the government announced a temporary ban on the export of face masks.<ref name=\"BBCTW06Feb2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51363132 |title=Coronavirus: Does China have enough face masks to meet its needs? |date=6 February 2020 |website=[[BBC News Online]] |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209150926/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51363132 |archive-date=9 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 6 February, the government instituted a mask rationing system.<ref name=\"tw_ration\">{{cite news |last1=Ku |first1=Chuan |last2=Kao |first2=Evelyn |title=WUHAN VIRUS/Taiwan approves new rationing system for surgical masks |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002030019 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=3 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205134424/https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202002030019 |archive-date=5 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Taiwan has been producing ten million masks per day since mid-March.<ref name=\"focus_tw\"/> On April 1, passengers on trains and intercity buses were required to wear face masks,<ref name=\"tw_tran_apr1\"/> unmasked riders facing a fine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lin |first1=Chia-nan |title=Virus Outbreak: Fines authorized for unmasked riders |url=https://taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2020/04/04/2003733965 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=4 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407180047/https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2020/04/04/2003733965 |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Turkey}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Turkey|Turkey]]: Residents will be required to wear masks at markets, as Turkish president announced.<ref>[https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/coronavirus-turkey-erdogan-youth-under-curfew-restrictions-curb-pandemic Coronavirus: Turkey imposes curfew on youth, shuts borders of 31 cities],<i>Middle East Eye</i>, 3{{nbsp}}April 2020.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Ukraine}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ukraine|Ukraine]]: Since April 6, wearing a face mask is required by the government in public places. In [[Kyiv]], public places were clarified to include parks and streets.<ref name=\"bbc_ua_apr6\">{{cite news |title=\u0423 \u043c\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0445 - \u0441\u043a\u0440\u0456\u0437\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0443\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0456, \u043d\u0430 \u0432'\u0457\u0437\u0434\u0456 \u043c\u0456\u0440\u044f\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0443\u0442\u044c \u0442\u0435\u043c\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0443. \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0456 \u043e\u0431\u043c\u0435\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0432 \u041a\u0438\u0454\u0432\u0456 |url=https://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/features-52173584 |date=5 April 2020 |work=BBC Ukraine |language=Ukrainian }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|US}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|United States]]: On April 6, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] recommended the wearing of non-medical cloth face coverings when in public places.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/diy-cloth-face-coverings.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=9 April 2020 |date=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Landsverk|first=Gabby|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-make-face-mask-at-home-no-sewing-coronavirus-2020-4|title=The CDC released a guide on how to make a face mask without sewing skills. Materials include a bandana, a coffee filter, and hair ties.|date=Apr 7, 2020|work=Business Insider|access-date=April 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Since April 17, residents of [[New York (state)|New York]] must wear masks in public.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first=Luis|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/15/nyregion/coronavirus-face-masks-andrew-cuomo.html|title=New York Orders Residents to Wear Masks in Public|date=2020-04-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-17|last2=Cramer|first2=Maria|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Uzbekistan}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uzbekistan|Uzbekistan]]: Officials made protective masks mandatory in all major cities in order to prevent the spread of coronavirus. Officials on March 22 said citizens not wearing masks in public in major cities would be fined $22 for the first offense and $67 for repeat offenses. <ref>[https://www.timesca.com/index.php/news/22276-afghanistan-reports-first-coronavirus-fatality-uzbekistan-makes-protective-masks-mandatory Afghanistan reports first coronavirus fatality, Uzbekistan makes protective masks mandatory],<i>The Times of Central Asia</i>, 23{{nbsp}}March 2020.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Venezuela}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Venezuela|Venezuela]]: T